In 2015, the Republican made headlines when he redecorated his Capitol Hill office in the style of Downton Abbey.
The indictment includes nine counts of wire fraud, five of falsification of election commission filings, six of filing false federal income tax returns, two of making false statements, and one each of mail fraud and theft of government funds.
Wire fraud alone carries a potential prison sentence of up to 20 years.
Mr Schock said in a statement: "As I have said before, we might have made errors among a few of the thousands and thousands of financial transactions we conducted, but they were honest mistakes - no one intended to break any law.
"I am eager to finally defend my name and reputation in a court of law and move on with my life."
The 35-year-old has been under investigation for 19 months, including by two grand juries that he said "poked, prodded and probed every aspect of my professional, political, and personal life".
George Terwilliger, Mr Schock's lawyer and a former Justice Department official, said: "This indictment will look bad, but underneath it is just made-up allegations of criminal activity arising from unintentional administrative errors.
"These charges are the culmination of an effort to find something, anything, to take down Aaron Schock."
