The former congressman said he had lost faith in "the integrity of our Justice Department".
"After this experience, I am forced to join millions of other Americans who have sadly concluded that our federal justice system is broken and too often driven by politics instead of facts," he said.
Mr Schock was a rising star of the GOP when he became embroiled in a series of press probes into his lavish spending.
While he repaid the government $40,000 (Â£28,500) for his aristocratic office renovation, it was the first in a series of reports by Politico and others about his use of public and campaign funds.
The Associated Press used geolocated data from the lawmaker's Instagram account and his flight records to raise discrepancies in more than $40,000 of expenses he claimed to cover the cost of private flights.
While the rules of the Congress allow legislators to use office funds this way, that was not the case in 2013, the year investigated by the AP.
Separately, Mr Schock came under scrutiny for multiple property deals closely related to political donors.
The former congressman resigned in March 2015.
He said he would leave Capitol Hill with "sadness and humility", adding that "God has a plan" for everyone.
